ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-1 The helicopter pilot took off at night on a positioning flight for an emergency medical service (EMS) operation. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-2 There were reports of a low overcast layer varying from 1,000 feet above ground level to the surface. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-3 The majority of the witnesses reported that the helicopter was flying low as it traveled over the ground and continued over water toward a nearby island. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-4 Subsequently, the helicopter collided with the water and sank. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-5 Several of the witnesses reported that the engine sounded normal until the helicopter crashed. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-6 Some witnesses reported a 'popping' sound or a 'laboring' sound from the engines; however, after the engines were recovered at a later date, no evidence of a preimpact mechanical failure or malfunction was found. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-7 Local residents reported that the water condition at the time of the accident was 'calm' or 'glassy.' 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-8 Several small pieces of the fuselage and main rotor blades were found floating on the surface of the water. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-9 Examination revealed that 3 of the main rotor blades had separated approximately three feet out from the attach points. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-10 The fourth blade separated approximately seven feet out from the attach point; however, the blade was bent and cracked chordwise approximately three feet out from the attach point. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-11 Using side scan sonar, wreckage was found over a distance of approximately 600 feet. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-12 The landing gear was found in the extended position, and the engine power levers were found in the flight position. 
ntsb2982txt-1-5-5-0-13 Also, torsional evidence was found on the tail rotor driveshaft. 
